title: The Bud Light Party Super Bowl Commercial (2016)
text:

Amy adds, "But, you know, gender identity is really a spectrum. And we don't need these labels." Seth follows: "Beer should have labels, NOT people." MY GRANDFATHER: When I was 12 years old, I received the single best piece of business advice. My grandfather is my hero, the person I look back to who is incredibly instrumental to my desire to be an entrepreneur. He was an entrepreneur and a builder, which is one of the reasons why I feel so passionate about building. It makes me feel close to him for just a second. He is one of the people that I wish I could go back in time and share my success with.¬†Every weekend I would go over to his house and help him work. He was an imposing figure, a powerful man. But radiation and chemotherapy did a number on his body when he had cancer. He lost the ability to work as hard as he used to. When I would go over on the weekends and help him, he would talk to me about life lessons he had learned and wanted me to know. He said something that I will never forget when it comes to business. You will feed your family or your ego, but you can't do both.

YOU NEED TO BE SWITZERLAND: If you don't hear anything else I say on this channel, hear this. Shut up and sell. You need to be Switzerland when it comes to business. Too many entrepreneurs think that their opinion needs to be expressed and that they need to feel good about what they're saying. They want to take a stand on an issue when the truth is you will alienate half of your potential customers. Alienating potential customers is why I never talk about politics or anything else controversial. I don't want to risk offending anybody I would otherwise do business with. If you understand this, you can sell your products or services to everybody. As a business person, you want to take everybody's money. It doesn't matter if they're conservative, liberal, white, black, or whomever; you shouldn't care.

PERSONAL VS PROFESSIONAL LIFE: When it comes to your personal life and what you talk about with your buddies, that's fine. But do not get in the business of telling people what you think. It will ruin your business's ability to be successful. The only business you need to be in regarding your front-facing persona is the business you're in. If people are coming to you to buy tee shirts, do not try to tell them how they should act, what they should do, or how they've oppressed somebody. If you're trying to sell somebody a cup of coffee, sell them a cup. Don't preach to them to get them to be like what you want them to be. If you take a stand or a stance, you will potentially alienate 50% of your audience.

DON'T BE AN IDIOT: A great example is the Dixie Chicks, which were tone-deaf in their music lyrics. They thought talking about President George W. Bush was a good idea. After one stupid comment, their fans scattered -- all because they chose to make a stand. Just because you have an audience doesn't mean you have a duty or responsibility to tell them what you want them to hear. Preaching to an audience is something that celebrities do all the time. They talk about what they're upset about and why you should feel this way. Do not get it twisted because your job is an entrepreneur and business person is to sell. You're either going to feed your ego or your family. You can't do both. You can donate and be as woke or unwoke as you want in your personal life, but when it comes to your business audience, you need to be like Switzerland. The more people you can bring into your orbit, the more potential to sell things to them. But you're an idiot if you decide to tell them what they should or should not think when it has nothing to do with your business.

title: Brilliant Marketing From Bud Light?
channelName: The Comments Section with Brett Cooper

title: Bud Light Backlash: 54% Support Bud Light Dylan Mulvaney Boycott
text:
Fifty-four percent of American adults support a boycott of Anheuser-Busch's Bud Light, according to polling from Rasmussen Reports.

Americans' desire to stop drinking Bud Light follows a furor that erupted a few weeks ago over the beer brand's decision to partner with controversial transgender social media influencer Dylan Mulvaney.

The entire controversy got kicked off when Mulvaney, a biological male who became popular on social media for a "365 Days of Girlhood" campaign that documented their gender transition over the course of a year, received a special edition can from Bud Light with Mulvaney's face on it as a gift for completing a full year of pretending to be a woman.

Mulvaney went on to share pictures of the can on social media, and also produced additional social media posts promoting Bud Light amid the then-ongoing NCAA Men's Division I basketball tournament, known colloquially as March Madness. One of the posts included Mulvaney in a bathtub blowing bubbles and sipping from a can of Bud Light.

title: Joe Rogan Fans TURN On Him For Defending Bud Light Trans Ad | The Kyle Kulinski Show
text:
Support The Show On Patreon!:
https://www.patreon.com/seculartalk

Subscribe to Krystal Kyle & Friends On Substack!:
https://krystalkyleandfriends.substac...

Follow Kyle on Twitter:
http://www.twitter.com/kylekulinski

"The first time I ever really listened to Kyle Kulinski‚Äôs show was in the back of a cab last summer. The driver had his phone hooked up through the stereo and was pumping out an episode through the car speakers ‚Äî loudly, as if looking to convert a captive audience.

‚ÄúDo you like Kyle Kulinski?‚Äù

The driver, Ahmed, was a recent immigrant and apparently a die-hard fan of Secular Talk, the political talk show that Kulinski broadcasts on YouTube. I told him, yes, in fact. I do like Kulinski, had come across his show several years ago, and, all things considered, he seemed pretty good.

‚ÄúHe understands what we‚Äôre up against,‚Äù Ahmed said. ‚ÄúLike Bernie.‚Äù

But I was surprised to hear Kulinski‚Äôs name mentioned in the same breath as Bernie Sanders, particularly with such adoration. Because what I did remember about Kulinski‚Äôs show struck me as mostly capital-P ‚Äúprogressive‚Äù takes on the news ‚Äî the left wing of the Netroots crowd more than the democratic socialism Sanders has popularized.

It‚Äôs an impression that wasn‚Äôt entirely incorrect.

‚ÄúI have no time for philosophical, airy bullshit,‚Äù Kulinski tells me from his home in Westchester, New York. ‚ÄúI don‚Äôt want to hear about Lenin. I don‚Äôt want to hear about Marx. I just want a super plainspoken, straightforward agenda with a straightforward way of selling it.‚Äù

With over 800,000 subscribers and nearly 670 million total views on YouTube, selling a progressive agenda is clearly something Kulinski knows how to do ‚Äî even Democracy Now, the long-standing flagship of progressive media, cannot match his reach on the platform. Chapo Trap House can certainly boast a wildly devoted fan base (and a not insignificant degree of media influence), but their audience is roughly half the size of Kulinski‚Äôs.

While Secular Talk might be more likely to be looped in with the progressive networks around Air America and Pacifica alums like Sam Seder than the more resolutely socialist world, Kulinski‚Äôs fiery rhetoric, razor-sharp class instincts, and knack for withering takedowns sets him apart from his peers. Judging by his rhetoric alone, he‚Äôs closer to a Eugene Debs than a Chris Hayes.

But unlike Hayes, Amy Goodman, or his friend Cenk Uygur of The Young Turks ‚Äî who began airing Secular Talk on his web network seven years ago ‚Äî the thirty-two-year-old Kulinski is virtually invisible in the mainstream media. Despite his enormous fan base, his show has never once been mentioned in the obligatory trend pieces on ‚Äúthe Millennial Left‚Äù pumped out by the prestige media. Nor has Kulinski‚Äôs name ever popped up at all in the New York Times, Vox, the New Yorker, New York Magazine, or the Washington Post, despite his leading role in cofounding Justice Democrats, the organization widely credited with sweeping Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez and the rest of ‚Äúthe Squad‚Äù to power.

Just last week, his Wikipedia page was deleted. The reason? ‚ÄúThere is very simply no [reliable source] coverage of this person,‚Äù according to one moderator. In new media, he‚Äôs king ‚Äî the Sean Hannity of the Berniecrat left. In old media, he‚Äôs nobody.

I suspect there are a few reasons for that. There is nothing ‚Äúcool‚Äù about Kulinski‚Äôs show. (As a friend put it, ‚Äú‚ÄòWelcome to Secular Talk‚Äô sounds like something you‚Äôd hear on Egyptian radio.‚Äù) His no-nonsense social-democratic politics won‚Äôt get him much cred with the Full Communism crowd. He records his show not in Brooklyn or Los Angeles, but in a studio he built himself in his modest Westchester home. His hair is too groomed and his taste in clothes too preppy to qualify as ‚ÄúDirtbag Left.‚Äù Nor has he ever attended an n+1 release party. ‚ÄúNot only have I not attended one,‚Äù he says, ‚ÄúI have no idea what that means.‚Äù

And yet he‚Äôs astonishingly plugged-in for a young man in the suburbs. Wondering how Sanders ended up on the Joe Rogan Experience? Kulinski, a frequent guest on Rogan‚Äôs wildly popular show, introduced them. ‚ÄúYou make the most sense to me,‚Äù Rogan told Kulinski on a recent episode. ‚ÄúYou‚Äôre a normal person.‚Äù

Much like Sanders himself, Kulinski‚Äôs show has a massive audience that just doesn‚Äôt compute with our media‚Äôs understanding of ‚Äúwhat the kids want‚Äù or even ‚Äúwhat the left-wing kids want.‚Äù

It‚Äôs probably for the best ‚Äî the very woke and very WASP-ish decorum haunting much of the media world is nowhere to be found in Secular Talk. ‚ÄúCorporate Democrats over-focus on identity as a trick to divert you from the issues that unite us all ‚Äî class issues,‚Äù he said on a recent episode.

title: Alissa Heinerscheid, VP, Bud Light | Make Yourself at Home, Episode 21
text:
At work, Alissa Heinerscheid is the Vice President of Bud Light, tasked with evolving and elevating an iconic brand that was in decline ‚Äî and she‚Äôs the first woman to lead Bud Light in the brand‚Äôs 40 year history. 

At home, she‚Äôs a mom who celebrates her kids‚Äô wins with a family swag chain, and a cancer survivor, who finds her joy paying it forward and coaching other women through the tough moments she's been through herself, like having her three kids through surrogacy. During Covid, she started a project called, 100 Women in 100 Days, asking each person, ‚Äúwhat‚Äôs in your worry box?‚Äù 

She says, in both work and home, her values are the same ‚Äî she‚Äôs motivated by the hard, and she‚Äôs always looking for depth and meaning.

On Sunday, Republican Senator Lindsey Graham called out Marjorie Taylor Green for defending Jake Tahara, the, uh, Pentagon Leaker, who Marjorie Taylor Green is trying to hold up as some kind of whistleblower, even though he, uh, wasn't leaking documents to expose crimes by the federal government or really even exposed lies by the federal government. He put our national security and the national security of multiple other countries at risk by leaking this information, not to the press, but to his friends on a message board so that he could seem cool. There's nothing whistleblower about that. So Lindsey Graham on the Sunday morning talk shows, rightfully called out Marjorie Taylor Green and all of the other Republicans that are fending, uh, uh, defending to Sherra for leaking this information to his buddies. And Marjorie Taylor Green, of course, is not one to take any kind of criticism lightly. 

She will lash out in the harshest way possible. So on Sunday evening, Marjorie Taylor Green tweeted out a photoshopped image of Lindsay Graham next to CNN n Host Dana Bash at a bar holding up one of those Bud Light cans featuring transgender influencer Dylan Mulvaney. Now, she didn't add a caption, she just tweeted out the picture. That's it. That was her response. Trying to, I guess, somehow imply that either Lindsay Graham actually supports the rights of L G B T Q people, which, I mean, would that be a bad thing if he did it? I know it would be a bad thing in the eyes of Republicans, but that would be the best thing in the world if Lindsay Graham could jump on and be an ally to the L g BT Q community. So it's not really the burden that you think it is Marjorie, but it's also, as I said, a Photoshopped image. 

The original image, Lindsey Graham's just holding a pint of beer next to Dana Bash. It's from when he was running for president in uh, 2015. But that's what Marjorie Taylor Green thinks is a win, right? She couldn't defend her position on the merits. So she has her team, cuz I'm willing to bet she doesn't know how to use Photoshop. She has her team make up this image trying to trash Lindsey Graham as an ally of the l q community or perhaps perpetuating that criticism that maybe Lindsay Graham is, you know, somehow in the closet. We've heard that attack from both the left and the right for many, many, many years. But if you wanted to defend your point on the merits, you would've actually discussed your point. Marjorie, you don't have to result, uh, resort, excuse me, to this childish display of Photoshopping an image in order to smear a man while also perpetuating that conspiracy theory about his sexuality. 

That's a low blow. That's pretty gross actually, if you ask me. It's also pretty gross that you think holding a beer can, uh, depicting Dylan Mulvaney is somehow offensive. It's a promotional thing. Like why, why? I don't even know why Republicans are still freaking the hell out about this, but they are. Marjorie Taylor greed is trying to capitalize on it, telling her people through this photoshopped image that Lindsay Graham somehow on the other side of it, like none of it makes any sense, folks, but that's politics in 2023. Everything is stupid. Nothing makes any sense and nobody wants to talk about the real issues, especially people like Marjorie Taylor Green, who clearly don't even understand what the real issues are.

title: Bud Light Backlash After Partnering With Transgender Influencer Dylan Mulvaney!!
text:
Bud Light and Anheuser Busch have been facing backlash over their recent partnership with Dylan Mulvaney, a social media influencer with a history of controversial and offensive behavior online. Many people have criticized Bud Light for working with Mulvaney despite his history, arguing that it sends a message that such behavior is acceptable or excusable. Bud Light has since issued a statement in response to the backlash, stating that they "do not condone derogatory language or behavior of any kind" and that "we understand the concerns raised about a recent influencer partnership and we apologize for any offense that it may have caused." Despite this apology, it remains to be seen how the public will respond and whether the controversy will have a lasting impact on Bud Light's reputation. We discuss the ongoing backlash!

title: Bud Light - Ladies Night (1993)
text:
Bud has a long history of Marketing the Rainbow, which goes back at least two decades, when they started a collaboration with GLAAD. Yet, their communications have not always been subtle, or supportive.

In this classic commercial from 1993, four men in drag play out their game of make believe - in "Ladies' Night". 

AdRespect: "The ad isn't meant to parody transgendered persons or gays, it plays on the Ms. Doubtfire/Tootsie joke of obvious men dressing as women out of need - it's older than television. The campaign has been so successful it has run for many years and has carried variations that included Don Rickles mistakenly picking up one of the women. One variation that was shot but never aired included a Los Angeles drag queen."

title: Travis Tritt Boycotts Anheuser-Busch Including Bud Light, Takes a Stand Against Underage Advertising
text:
#travistritt #boycotts #anheuserbusch 

Country music star Travis Tritt has announced that he is dropping all Anheuser-Busch products, including Bud Light beer, due to the company's recent ad campaign featuring Dylan Mulvaney. Mulvaney, a competitive gamer, has been promoting Bud Light during his livestreams on Twitch, a popular video game streaming platform. Tritt took issue with the fact that Mulvaney has been promoting the beer to his underage audience, stating that it goes against his own values and morals.

Tritt said, "As a father and a grandfather, I find it completely unacceptable that Anheuser-Busch would use a minor to promote their products in this way. I have always been a strong advocate for responsible drinking, and I cannot in good conscience continue to support a company that is willing to exploit children for profit."

Tritt's decision has garnered mixed reactions from fans and industry professionals, with some praising his stance on responsible advertising, while others criticize his decision as an overreaction. Anheuser-Busch has not yet responded to Tritt's statement.

This move comes as Tritt prepares for his upcoming "No-Frills Classic Outlaw Country" tour, which kicks off later this month. It remains to be seen if Tritt's decision to drop Anheuser-Busch products will have any impact on his tour or future partnerships.

title: The WOKIES now HATE BUDLIGHT... APOLOGY BACKFIRE!
text:
Hello, in this video, I will be discussing an article from Time Magazine about the controversy surrounding a Bud Light commercial featuring Dylan Mulvaney, a transgender man. The commercial was part of Bud Light's "beer for everyone" campaign, which aimed to promote inclusivity and diversity.

The ad received a lot of backlash from certain consumers who expressed transphobic views and threatened to boycott the company. Despite the backlash, Bud Light initially stood by their decision to feature Mulvaney in the ad, stating that they were committed to promoting diversity and inclusion.

However, according to the article, members of the LGBTQ+ community felt that Bud Light did not adequately defend Mulvaney after the backlash intensified. Critics claimed that Bud Light could have done more to push back against transphobia and support their transgender spokesperson.

title: Jim Norton DESTROYS Conservative Outrage Over Bud Light Trans Ad | The Kyle Kulinski Show
text:
Support The Show On Patreon!:
https://www.patreon.com/seculartalk

Subscribe to Krystal Kyle & Friends On Substack!:
https://krystalkyleandfriends.substac...

Follow Kyle on Twitter:
http://www.twitter.com/kylekulinski

"The first time I ever really listened to Kyle Kulinski‚Äôs show was in the back of a cab last summer. The driver had his phone hooked up through the stereo and was pumping out an episode through the car speakers ‚Äî loudly, as if looking to convert a captive audience.

‚ÄúDo you like Kyle Kulinski?‚Äù

The driver, Ahmed, was a recent immigrant and apparently a die-hard fan of Secular Talk, the political talk show that Kulinski broadcasts on YouTube. I told him, yes, in fact. I do like Kulinski, had come across his show several years ago, and, all things considered, he seemed pretty good.

‚ÄúHe understands what we‚Äôre up against,‚Äù Ahmed said. ‚ÄúLike Bernie.‚Äù

But I was surprised to hear Kulinski‚Äôs name mentioned in the same breath as Bernie Sanders, particularly with such adoration. Because what I did remember about Kulinski‚Äôs show struck me as mostly capital-P ‚Äúprogressive‚Äù takes on the news ‚Äî the left wing of the Netroots crowd more than the democratic socialism Sanders has popularized.

It‚Äôs an impression that wasn‚Äôt entirely incorrect.

‚ÄúI have no time for philosophical, airy bullshit,‚Äù Kulinski tells me from his home in Westchester, New York. ‚ÄúI don‚Äôt want to hear about Lenin. I don‚Äôt want to hear about Marx. I just want a super plainspoken, straightforward agenda with a straightforward way of selling it.‚Äù

With over 800,000 subscribers and nearly 670 million total views on YouTube, selling a progressive agenda is clearly something Kulinski knows how to do ‚Äî even Democracy Now, the long-standing flagship of progressive media, cannot match his reach on the platform. Chapo Trap House can certainly boast a wildly devoted fan base (and a not insignificant degree of media influence), but their audience is roughly half the size of Kulinski‚Äôs.

While Secular Talk might be more likely to be looped in with the progressive networks around Air America and Pacifica alums like Sam Seder than the more resolutely socialist world, Kulinski‚Äôs fiery rhetoric, razor-sharp class instincts, and knack for withering takedowns sets him apart from his peers. Judging by his rhetoric alone, he‚Äôs closer to a Eugene Debs than a Chris Hayes.

But unlike Hayes, Amy Goodman, or his friend Cenk Uygur of The Young Turks ‚Äî who began airing Secular Talk on his web network seven years ago ‚Äî the thirty-two-year-old Kulinski is virtually invisible in the mainstream media. Despite his enormous fan base, his show has never once been mentioned in the obligatory trend pieces on ‚Äúthe Millennial Left‚Äù pumped out by the prestige media. Nor has Kulinski‚Äôs name ever popped up at all in the New York Times, Vox, the New Yorker, New York Magazine, or the Washington Post, despite his leading role in cofounding Justice Democrats, the organization widely credited with sweeping Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez and the rest of ‚Äúthe Squad‚Äù to power.

Just last week, his Wikipedia page was deleted. The reason? ‚ÄúThere is very simply no [reliable source] coverage of this person,‚Äù according to one moderator. In new media, he‚Äôs king ‚Äî the Sean Hannity of the Berniecrat left. In old media, he‚Äôs nobody.

I suspect there are a few reasons for that. There is nothing ‚Äúcool‚Äù about Kulinski‚Äôs show. (As a friend put it, ‚Äú‚ÄòWelcome to Secular Talk‚Äô sounds like something you‚Äôd hear on Egyptian radio.‚Äù) His no-nonsense social-democratic politics won‚Äôt get him much cred with the Full Communism crowd. He records his show not in Brooklyn or Los Angeles, but in a studio he built himself in his modest Westchester home. His hair is too groomed and his taste in clothes too preppy to qualify as ‚ÄúDirtbag Left.‚Äù Nor has he ever attended an n+1 release party. ‚ÄúNot only have I not attended one,‚Äù he says, ‚ÄúI have no idea what that means.‚Äù

And yet he‚Äôs astonishingly plugged-in for a young man in the suburbs. Wondering how Sanders ended up on the Joe Rogan Experience? Kulinski, a frequent guest on Rogan‚Äôs wildly popular show, introduced them. ‚ÄúYou make the most sense to me,‚Äù Rogan told Kulinski on a recent episode. ‚ÄúYou‚Äôre a normal person.‚Äù

Much like Sanders himself, Kulinski‚Äôs show has a massive audience that just doesn‚Äôt compute with our media‚Äôs understanding of ‚Äúwhat the kids want‚Äù or even ‚Äúwhat the left-wing kids want.‚Äù

It‚Äôs probably for the best ‚Äî the very woke and very WASP-ish decorum haunting much of the media world is nowhere to be found in Secular Talk. ‚ÄúCorporate Democrats over-focus on identity as a trick to divert you from the issues that unite us all ‚Äî class issues,‚Äù he said on a recent episode.

title: Senate panel passes bill to ban transgender girls from girls sports in NC
text:
North Carolina took its first step to join more than 20 other states in banning transgender girls from playing on girls' sports teams in middle school and high school Tuesday morning.

If enacted into law, transgender girls would be prohibited from participating in sports that correspond with their gender identity under a bill that advanced Tuesday in the North Carolina Senate.

The Senate education committee advanced the "Fairness in Women's Sports Act" on a voice vote with Republicans on the panel saying such a blanket ban is necessary to protect biological girls and saying that the small number of transgender girls, estimated at 15, currently participating in North Carolina is too many.

*This transcript was generated by a third-party transcription software company, so please excuse any typos.

A nonprofit conservative group called Consumers Research has launched a new app that will let shoppers know which products they want to buy are woke, so that of course they can avoid those products. To put it another way, a conservative group has put together this app so that other conservatives don't have to worry about any products that might hurt their little feelings because there's such snowflakes that, God forbid you buy a product from a company that doesn't 100% share your values. That's how terrified Republicans are of buying these so-called woke products. Even though not a single person there on the right can tell you what woke actually means. Now here's the thing. These corporations that Republicans are going after, you know it, it doesn't matter if it's Anheuser-Busch, it doesn't matter if it's, you know, the coolers, the coffee makers, uh uh, the shoes, the other beverages, the books. 

A lot of the parent companies of these products share the same values as Republicans. Like we don't think people should have time off work. We think we should be able to pay them lower than minimum wage. We don't want to have have to offer benefits to them while they work for us. We don't wanna have to do anything to keep them safe. We wanna be able to pay them below minimum wage. That's what a lot of these companies that Republicans are now boycotting stand for, which is pretty much what the Republican Party stands for. The only area where there's a slight bit of difference, and most of that difference really is just for the cameras, is on social issues. That's it. But social issues are the only thing that matters to Republicans these days. It's a losing issue for them. They're not doing well with it. They're going to get trounced in 2024 because of it, but here they are with a new app that will let them take it and run with it. 

Do what you gotta do, guys. Listen, vote with your dollars. I get it. But think about this for a second. Republicans are out there boycotting, you know, whether it's books or coolers or coffee makers or beers, because those products at one point said, Hey, you know what? Let's kind of be inclusive a little bit. That's it. Now, when, when people on the left, when the progressives go out there and boy, uh, boycott a company, it's because, hey, this company just dumped these cancer causing toxins into the river and a hundred thousand people are gonna die in the next 20 years. Or, Hey, this company is so bad, they're making people pee in jars and not letting them get a break so they can go to the bathroom. It's a crap company. Let's not shop there. 

So do you see the difference between the boycotts on the left and the right? The right is like, oh my God, a transgender person is drinking Bud Light. Now I have to hate them, versus liberals or leftists who say, you know what? It's probably not a good idea to shop at a company that's making people pee and bottles because they're mistreating them so badly. But even then, we don't have to have a little app on our phone to tell us, oh no, you're touching a bad product. You know why? Because we're not the ones who are the delicate little snowflakes. That distinction rest with conservatives alone.

title: Bud Light Embraces Trans Community, Kid Rock Responds with Violence
text:
Vile. Disgusting. Dangerous. Kid Rock seems to hate trans people and really hate their being associated with a beer company. To prove it, he posted an extremely violent video on Twitter. 
Rock, whose real name is Robert James Richie, seems angry that Anheuser-Busch, which owns Bud Light, is embracing the trans community, specifically social media influencer Dylan Mulvaney. She‚Äôs partnered with them for a clever social media campaign promoting a sports-related contest where she hugs cans of Bud Light and shows off a one-of-a-kind can with her face on it. 
The contrast is clear: Her video is light, tongue-in-cheek fun. Kid Rock‚Äôs is the opposite. He avoids making a verbal connection but the message was clear to his followers - who posted equally vile support in the comments section. More than eight million people viewed the video in the first two days.
At a time when lawmakers support legal discrimination against trans, this type of video from a rough, conservative rock star becomes especially dangerous, sending a message that could be interpreted that violence against trans people and their allies is justified.
What are they scared of? Apparently this. This is video from Trans Day of Visibility last week at the Pride Center in Wilton Manors. There were musical performances, poetry readings and more. Trans people contribute to society like everybody else, while being threatened every step of the way.
As for Mulvaney, she hasn‚Äôt responded to Rock‚Äôs video, but has posted, ‚ÄúIf you are in a position of power to hire someone trans or non-binary, please do! We need to exist in every space. I want to see trans people doing all the brand deals.‚Äù
If that happens, Kid Rock‚Äôs head will explode faster than those cases of Bud Light.
Fun facts: Bud products are prominently featured on the menu of his Nashville restaurant.
Also: While she has about 1.7 million followers on Instagram, he has fewer than a million. Sounds like a case of Follower Envy.

title: Man in viral Walmart beer-smashing video, charged with exposing himself to teen | New York Post
text:
A man who was seen in a viral Walmart video smashing cases of Busch Light beer in Kansas has been charged with exposing himself to a minor, according to police.

J. Dustin David Cain, 44, of Topeka, was arrested Monday night after causing a commotion at the Walmart on SW Wanamaker Road.

A TikTok video that has now been viewed more than 306,000 times shows a man, later identified as Cain, removing cases of beer from a Walmart beverage refrigerator and angrily throwing them to the floor.

When he notices that he is being filmed by an onlooker, he hurls a couple of loose beer cans into the distance, at one point narrowly missing the amateur cameraman, who is forced to dive for cover.

Police later arrive to arrest Cain, who is seen being led away in handcuffs.

Donald Trump may have some of the worst lawyers imaginable going to bat for him in the Eugene Carroll assault trial that is coming up on April 25th. And thanks to a judge's ruling yesterday, we know for a fact that it is coming up on April 25th, Donald Trump's attorneys, Joe Taina and Alina Haba had filed a motion with the court recently saying, Hey, listen, judge Lewis Kaplan, I don't know if you've noticed this, but our client, Donald J. Trump is, is going through some very publicized legal problems in Manhattan, and so we would like to delay this assault trial even further so that things can cool down a bit. Judge Lewis Kaplan said, no, I'm not going to do that. This, this doesn't affect this trial. We're moving forward. April 25th is the start date. Now, specifically, Trump's lawyers had said, quote, the threat to President Trump's rights is particularly dire because the coverage of the indictment has repeated a salacious and false allegations. 

They did misspell that exactly what Ms. Carroll alleges in this case. So you didn't even bother to spell check your complaint or your motion. You submitted it anyway. You didn't offer any real reasons just other than, Hey, our guy's going through some stuff. Yikes. I don't know if you've seen it, it's pretty bad. But that's what happens when you're representing an individual that is facing investigations from multiple different bodies in multiple different states. You know, sorry for you. But that doesn't have any impact on the specific case here. Now, if this lawsuit that Eugene Carroll had filed was about financial crimes, then that might actually make sense to delay it a little bit while the other stuff dies down. But this has nothing to do with money. The two cases could not be further apart in subject matter. One of them is potentially a sexual assault. The other is falsifying business records to cover up an affair, a consensual affair. So if it makes your client look bad, that's not Eugene Carroll's fault. That is not Judge Kaplan's fault. Yes, the jury is gonna know those things, but you know what else? Donald Trump's legal team, the jury is also gonna be aware of everything Donald Trump said and did during four years as president of the United States. They're aware of the comments that he made on January 6th, 2021 at the stop the steal rally. They're aware of the posts that he makes on truth social. 

They're aware of everything the man has done, and there's nothing you can do to change that. For most people, watching the indictments come out of New York didn't necessarily change their opinion of them. For a lot of people, it just confirmed what they had already believed. For the record, this the second time in two business days that Donald Trump's lawyers have been shot down by Judge Kaplan. They were also shot down last Friday when they attempted to get the judge to unmask the jury, which is going to remain anonymous. And the judge of course said no. So they're lost on Friday. They lost on Monday, and now they've got one week till they have to go sit in that trial, where based on their past performances, it's probably a good chance they're gonna lose again. But this one is gonna be very impactful for Donald Trump.
